    "summary": "The origins of the Kerma culture lie in the fourth millennium BCE, in the region of Upper Nubia centered on the Nile bend near present-day Kerma in Sudan. Precursors to the classic Kerma kingdom are traceable to pre-Kerma pastoral communities that herded cattle along the Nile and its tributaries, establishing settlements and cemeteries that would grow into the foundations of the first indigenous sub-Saharan African state.\n\nBy the third millennium BCE, Kerma had developed into a significant center of trade, cattle herding, and craft production, linked to [[event:1637|Egypt]] through exchange of gold, ivory, and enslaved people. Kerma-period pottery, characterized by its fine black-topped red ware, is among the most technically accomplished ceramics of ancient Africa. The culture would eventually give rise to the Kingdom of Kerma (approximately 2500–1500 BCE), which became a rival power to the Egyptian Middle Kingdom and the first recognizably urban civilization in sub-Saharan Africa.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerma_culture",
